metadata.name: Drifters #7
metadata.description:
In an undiscovered area, you've stumbled upon an unknown creature.
It looks weirdly haunting, and you're feeling a sense of unease.

You're wondering what it's doing.

It seems to move in patterns, and sometimes suddenly changes course.
Is it communicating?

(to whom?)

Setting aside your discomfort for a moment, you're realizing you could be seeing it wrong.
While the creature does look eerie and its motivations are unclear,
you realize every culture has its own appreciation of aesthetics,
and you can't help noticing there is a certain grace to this performance.

And it all makes sense.

You're witnessing uncharted explorations of elegance.

–

Append [?scale=<number>] to the url to scale the renderer.
Press [control / command + s] to save the current frame to a file.

© 2022 Monokai.

metadata.name: Ornithic #274
metadata.description:
Pure p5.js code. No svg, no image, no other materials. Creating code arts with polar coordinate system and algorithms are my passion. This generative art contains a lot of features that may be rare than common.  

• 30 color palettes // 2 of them have 3 different colors
• 4 grass structures // With the same algorithm 
• 16 flower types //  Count, leaf number and size
• 6 color functions // Different colorizations with b&w 

Also, the outputs of the project are very high resolution to print or something like that.
April / 2022
Rhaegar

metadata.name: Subdivisions #61
metadata.description:
As an artist with a background in engineering, I have always been a fan of technical drawings.
Architectural sketches and renderings fascinate me with their ability to visualize the conceptual.

I create generative art for the same reason - to reveal the beauty in an algorithm.

This project represents the division of space using techniques that, for me, call to mind sitting
at a drafting table, straight edge in hand, imagining what might be possible.

You can export a high resolution PNG (5000x5000) by pressing the 'e' key.

Twitter: @jeffpalmer
https://jpalmer.dev

metadata.name: On the sea, I ... #63
metadata.description:
Generative painting based on churning waves with floating buoys. Represented in three different media.

Features:
- Three drawing styles: "watercolor" 70%, "brush" 30%, or "block" 70%
- Warm white or blue waves
- Variable border and column sizes
- Number of columns
- Calm waves at the edges or center
- Color 80% or red 20% buoys
- Buoy drawing style, "watercolor" or "brush"

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.
Press ’s’ to save a screenshot. Image size is 928x1200px
Press ’p’ to pause/resume.

Add '&size=#' to the end of the live view URL to render a variation of your edition at a resolution up to 3,000 px.

metadata.name: Caustics #15
metadata.description:
Domain warped noise and circles simulating the caustic effects of light through a column of water. The pattern is rendered by two passes of variable poisson sampling.

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.
Press ’s’ to save a screenshot. Image size is 928x1200px
Press ’p’ to pause/resume.

Add '&size=#' to the end of the live view URL to render a variation of your edition at a resolution up to 5,000 px.

Common Features:
- 40+ color palettes
- 50/50 color or black and white
- If color, 50/50 full color or mono + right color palette
- Dark or light background
- Variable number of bubbles
- Variable spacing between bubbles
- Pattern intensity through bubbles
- Pattern banding

Rare
- 20% dark with duotone palettes of grey + gold, bronze, or blue

metadata.name: winter trees #5
metadata.description:
I once took an Amtrak train from New York City to Portland, Oregon in the winter. This seemed like it would be exciting. It was not. However, one moonlit night in North Dakota, I was gazing out the window and saw a small clump of trees, with the full moon over them. I quickly snapped a picture, which I still have, and which is my fondest memory of this trip. This is a recreation of this image in generative code. 

Created in p5.js

metadata.name: RIBBON FIELDS //GENESIS #3
metadata.description:
RIBBON FIELDS //GENESIS


RIBBON FIELDS //GENESIS is a series of generative projects. This is the first one in the series but also my very first one ever. This is my genesis, I hope you like it.

In RIBBON FIELDS //GENESIS, you see a delicate balance between light (colorful lines that simply move along trying to survive) and darkness (darker lines trying to erase the colored ones) moving along a flow field. I iterated a couples of times before finding the best mix between light, dark, balance but also a bit of mystery.

If you end up getting one of my pieces (thanks in advance 👌!) come tell me what did you like about it.

----

Hello, I'm Mauro, a developer by day and generative artist by night working from Switzerland. I started doing generative art because it's at the intersection of some of my interests: coding, math/physics and art. I'm still trying to get good with that last one.

You can find me on twitter @95_percent_ so come say hello.

metadata.name: Oniric Spaces #97
metadata.description:
As my dreams, mixing memories form my childhood, others from my architecture studies at university and my daily life.
_The investigations of the neoplasticism in the architecture as a set of floating planes that define reality.
_The nature of architectural drawings as a thinking tool, the dirtiness of a sketch mixed with the clarity of the ideas that want to show.
_The origin of computer graphics, the 80s demoscene (neon / trance / post punk / sci-fi ), the time where "digital" was a value by itself.
_The dynamic nature of dreams where spaces are moving and steady at the same time.

metadata.name: Hashed Cities #164
metadata.description:
This token generates a deterministic set of minimal, abstract buildings of varying widths, heights, transparencies, and patterns, assembling a skyline view of your own unique imaginary city. Each city comes with its own randomized city day.

Each mint has a native setting (Day or Night) which combined with the current time of viewing influences real-time movements of celestial bodies in your mint, e.g. on a mint with the Day setting, the sun will only appear when viewed during the day. The piece will re-render every minute.

The individual strokes of this token feature some of my latest developments of an algorithm that generatively simulates the texture of print imperfections. They are randomized at each render to give it a unique character. Note that depending on the complexity of each mint, some renders may introduce a brief pause. The aesthetics are greatly inspired by plotter art of early computer artists such as 'City Painting' by Grace C. Hertlein.

Made in p5js
Created Nov 2021
Artist: @Yazid
